{{Infobox artifact | name = Armazi stele of Serapit | image = [[File:Armazi Bilingual.jpg|280px]] | image2 = | image_caption = | material = [[Stone]] | size = | writing = [[Ancient Greek]] and [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] | created = 150 AD | discovered = 1940 | place = [[Armazi]] | location = [[Georgian National Museum]], [[Tbilisi]] | id = }} The '''Armazi stele of Serapit''' ({{lang-ka|სერაფიტას არმაზის სტელა}}) or '''Armazi bilingual''' ({{lang-ka|არმაზის ბილინგვა}}) is a funerary [[stele]] with [[bilingual inscription]]s written in [[Ancient Greek]] and [[Armazic language|Armazic]], a local idiom of [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]], found in 1940, at [[Armazi]], near [[Mtskheta]], in the ancient capital of the [[Kingdom of Iberia]]. The stele [[Memorialization|memorialises]] a short-lived Georgian princess named Serapit.<ref>Lang, p. 4</ref> The inscriptions mention Georgian monarchs, [[Pharnavaz I of Iberia]] and [[Pharasmanes II of Iberia]], and other members of [[aristocracy]]. The inscriptions are dated 150 AD.<ref name="Rapp">Rapp, p. 216</ref><ref>Lang, p. 5</ref>
==Inscriptions== ===Ancient Greek inscription=== {{cquote|Serapeitis, daughter of Zeouach the Younger, pitiaxes, wife of Iodmanganos, son of Publicius Agrippa, pitiaxes, who won many battles as ''[[epitropos]]'' of the great king of the Iberians, Xepharnougos. She died, younger than twenty-one years, who had inimitable beauty.<ref name="Rapp"/>}}
===Aramaic inscription=== {{cquote|I am Serapit, daughter of Zewah the Younger, pitiaxes of King [[Pharasmanes II of Iberia|Pharasmanes]], wife of Yodmangan the victorious and winner of many victories, master of the court of King Xepharnougos and the son of Agrippa, master of the court of King Pharasmanes, victorious over the mighty, which [[Pharnavaz I of Iberia|Pharnavaz]] could not accomplish. Serapit was so fine and beautiful that no one was her equal in beauty. And she died in her twenty-first year.<ref name="Rapp"/>}}
