{{Maya civilization}}
'''Itzan''' is a [[Maya civilization|Maya]] archaeological site located in the [[Municipalities of Guatemala|municipality]] of [[La Libertad, El Petén|La Libertad]] in the [[Petén Department]] of [[Guatemala]].<ref name=Ponciano1991-232>Ponciano 1991, p.232.</ref> Various small structures at the site were destroyed in the 1980s during oil exploration activities by Sonpetrol and Basic Resources Ltd, prompting rescue excavations by archaeologists.<ref name=Ponciano1991-232/> In spite of its small size, the site appears to have been the most politically important centre in its area, as evidenced by its unusually large quantity of monuments and the size of its major architecture.<ref>Ponciano 1991, pp.234-235.</ref>

The site was first occupied in the [[Mesoamerican chronology|Middle Preclassic]], with occupation continuing to the [[Mesoamerican chronology|Late Classic]].<ref>Román de León & Johnston 1992, pp.50, 54.</ref>

==Location==
The ruins are {{convert|25|km|mi}} northwest of the [[Dos Pilas]] archaeological site on the bank of a minor tributary of the [[Pasion River]].<ref name=Sharer387>Sharer & Traxler 2006 , p.387.</ref><ref>Coe 1999, p.152.</ref> The city was on a natural hilltop surrounded by ravines and seasonal swamps.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234>Ponciano 1991, p.234.</ref> The tributary of the Pasion River has its origin in [[Laguna Itzan]], a small lake to the east of the site.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> A spring to the west of the site appears to have been a permanent watersource for the city.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> Itzan is situated roughly halfway between the Classic Period cities of [[Altar de Sacrificios]] and [[Seibal]], and is located about {{convert|14|km|mi}} northeast of the former.<ref name=Roman50>Román de León & Johnston 1992, p.50.</ref><ref>Houston, p.3.</ref> The site is located approximately {{convert|50|km|mi}} west of the modern town of [[Sayaxché]] and {{convert|8|km|mi}} north of the Pasion River.<ref name=Roman50/>

==History==
Itzan was continuously occupied from the Middle Preclassic through to the Late Classic, with much reduced activity during the Early Classic, with the latter period only being evidenced by a single burial accompanied by a ceramic plate.<ref>Román de León & Johnston 1992, p.56.</ref>

Hieroglyphic Stairway 2 at the Late Classic period kingdom of Dos Pilas records that in 652 AD the powerful city of [[Calakmul]] seized control of Itzan,<ref>Fahsen et al 2003, p.689.</ref> and Dos Pilas itself also won a major victory over the city.<ref>Demarest 2006, p.139.</ref> Itzan may also have gone to war against [[El Chorro (Maya site)|El Chorro]].<ref>Houston, p.4.</ref>

A [[lady of Itzan|noblewoman from Itzan]] became the main wife of  [[B'alaj Chan K'awiil]], a king of Dos Pilas, and their son was [[Itzamnaaj B'alam|Itzamnaaj Balam]].<ref name=Sharer387/> The collapse of the aggressive Dos Pilas kingdom in the late 8th century AD apparently benefited Itzan, which then experienced a period of renewed activity.<ref>Martin & Grube 2000, p. 65.</ref>

The site was discovered in February 1968 by Dennis and Louisa Wheeler, two [[Peace Corps]] volunteers.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> The ruins were then explored by archaeologists of the [[Seibal|Ceibal Project]] in 1978, who only spent a few hours at the site.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/>

==Site description==
Itzan was a small city but was considered by archaeologists to have characteristics that made excavation worthwhile.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> Initial investigations recorded a number of carved monuments and large structures, some standing up to {{convert|7|m|ft}} high.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> The site core was mapped in 1986, when archaeologists noted that a number of carved monuments had been damaged by looters and that some of the buildings had been cut by looters' trenches.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> Various monument pieces that had been cut by looters were transferred to the departmental capital [[Flores, El Petén|Flores]] with the intention of later moving them to [[Guatemala City]].<ref>Ponciano 1991, p.235.</ref>

The centre of the site is grouped around the North and South Plazas, both of which are open plazas, and the closed West and East Plazuelas which are completely enclosed by architecture.<ref>Román de León & Johnston 1992, p.52.</ref>

The site core includes a formal acropolis, large plazas and a large amount of [[stele|stelae]] and altars, totalling at least 25 monuments, all of which have been moved from their original locations by looters in order to excavate below them.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> Most of these monuments were originally positioned in open plazas in front of the largest structures.<ref name=Ponciano1991-234/> The remains of [[Maya writing|hieroglyphic texts]] were found associated with the North and South Stairways of the West Plaza.<ref>Ponciano 1991, pp.234-235.</ref> Much of the Late Classic period acropolis was built upon earlier Preclassic structures.<ref>Román de León & Johnston 1992, pp.54-55.</ref>

The site periphery between {{convert|3.6|to|4|km|mi}} south of the site core included at least three groups of simple perishable Late Classic residential structures laid out around central patios, without being built upon platforms, suggesting that the population of the site was greater than initially thought based on the site's monumental architecture.<ref>Johnston et al 1992, pp.131, 134, 144.</ref> The entire settled area of Itzan occupies a ridge in a strip about {{convert|300|m|ft}} wide by {{convert|7|km|mi}} long, with the site core being situated near the centre of this zone.<ref>Johnston et al 1992, p.134.</ref> A modern road cuts through the area of settlement.<ref>Johnston et al 1992, p.134.</ref>

'''Stela 17''' includes a hieroglyphic text that mentions lords of Itzan and of the nearby city of Altar de Sacrificios. It also contains a section of damaged text that may indicate warfare between Itzan and the site of El Chorro.<ref>Houston, pp.3-4.</ref>

'''Stela 20''' is fragmented. A large piece was found to the northwest of the acropolis.<ref>Román de León & Johnston 1992, p.55.</ref>

