'''Margrit Brückner''' (born 1946) is a [[feminism|feminist]] [[Germany|German]] [[sociology|sociologist]] and a retired professor of the [[Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences]]. Her publications on girls and women at work, and, especially, her work on violence against women, have become core academic texts. Another of her more notable specialities involves her contributions to the international debate on [[care work |(social) care]].<ref name="Bock2015">{{cite book|author=Ulla Bock|title= Margrit Brückner |work=Pionierarbeit: Die ersten Professorinnen für Frauen- und Geschlechterforschung an deutschsprachigen Hochschulen 1984-2014| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B-TDBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA258|date=2 April 2015|publisher=Campus Verlag| isbn=978-3-593-50301-1|pages=258–259}}</ref><ref name=MBlautTSP>{{cite web|title= Power für die Frauen|work=Tony-Sender-Preis .... Alle zwei Jahre verleiht die Stadt Frankfurt zu Ehren der Frauenrechtlerin Tony Sender den gleichnamigen Preis. In diesem Jahr findet die Verleihung am 29. November, Tony Senders 125. Geburtstag statt. Der Preis geht an Margrit Brückner. |url= https://www.journal-frankfurt.de/index.php?src=journal_news&rubrik=2&rubrik_rewrite=Panorama&id=20304&id_rewrite=Tony-Sender-Preis-Power-fuer-die-Frauen&login=1&theme=npgreen#sozial_kommentar|date=29 November 2013|publisher=Presse Verlagsgesellschaft für Zeitschriften und neue Medien mbH (Journal Frankfurt)| accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=MBiGmJG>{{cite web|title=Interview with Margrit Brückner, Ethics of Care Conference| date= 2013| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mqLiIe1D-yY|author=Johanna Gröne (interviewer)|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=WohlfahrtsregimenlautMB>{{cite web|title=Der gesellschaftliche Umgang mit menschlicher Hilfsbedürftigkeit| work=Fürsurge und Pflege in westlichen Wohlfahrtsregimen|date=1 June 2004|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs11614-004-0011-9| author=Margrit Brückner|publisher= Springer International Publishing AG., CH-Cham|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>
== Life == Margrit Brückner was born during the [[Aftermath of World War II|aftermath of war]] at [[Mennighüffen]]<ref name="Bock2015"/> or [[Rinteln]],<ref name=MBlautTSP/> in the countryside between [[Bielefeld]] and [[Hannover]]. She studied [[Sociology]] at [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz|Mainz]], [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt]] and the [[London School of Economics]] between 1966 and 1972.<ref name="Bock2015"/> In 1979 she accepted an appointment as a Professor for Sociology and Women's Studies at the [[Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences|Fachhochschule Frankfurt am Main (as the Applied Sciences University was then known)]]. At Frankfurt she participated actively in the [[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund|Socialist Student League]]. In 1969 she joined with others to establish the first "Frankfurt Women's Council" (''"Frankfurter Weiberrat"''),<ref name=MBlautTSP/> described later by one authority as "the nucleus of the Frankfurt women's movement".<ref name=DankesredeMB>{{cite web|work="... dem Nukleus der Frankfurter Frauenbewegung"|pages=19-22|title=Tony Sender Preis ... Dankesrede von Margrit Brückner|date=September 2014|publisher=Frauenreferat Frankfurt am Main|url=https://www.frankfurt.de/sixcms/media.php/738/Dokumentation-Tony-Sender-Preis_2013.pdf|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>
As a sixteen year old she had been a beneficiary of a new schools exchange programme and spent time at a school in a small town in the [[United States]], enabling her to improve her English language skills and acclimatize to the very different unwritten social rules governing the behaviour of school-age girls.<ref name=DankesredeMB/> She returned across the Atlantic after receiving her first degree, undertaking a two year research stay at the Institute for the Study of Social Change ([[University of California]]). Brückner then received her doctorate from [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt University]] in 1983. Adumbrating her subsequent academic career, her [[:de:Elisabeth-Selbert-Preis|prize-winning]]<ref name=MBlautFHSF/> dissertation was entitled "Liebe der Frauen – über das Verhältnis von Weiblichkeit und Misshandlung" (''loosely "Love of women - on the relationship of the female condition and abuse"'').<ref name=MBlautFHSF>{{cite web|title=Margrit Brückner macht häusliche Gewalt sichtbar: Die Pionierin wird mit Symposium verabschiedet|work= Pressemitteilung von: Fachhochschule Frankfurt am Main|date=22 June 2012|url=https://www.openpr.de/news/642878/Margrit-Brueckner-macht-haeusliche-Gewalt-sichtbar-Die-Pionierin-wird-mit-Symposium-verabschiedet.html|publisher=Fachhochschule Frankfurt am Main|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> She also trained to become group analyst and supervisor (''" Gruppenanalytikerin und Supervisorin"''), terms which even she has subsequently struggled to translate into English.<ref name=MBiGmJG/> It was again at [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt University]] that in 2000 she received her [[habilitation]] (higher academic qualification), also receiving [[:de:Lehrberechtigung |"Venia legendi" (''loosely: "teaching rights"'')]] in [[Sociology]]. She has continued to teach and support sociology students at [[Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences|the Hochschule in Frankfurt]] up to and beyond her retirement in 2012.<ref name=MBlautTSP/> Her research and campaigning work has continued to focus on care-work and care-networks, along with the life situations of women working in the sexual services field.
Since 2001, with Monika Simmel-Joachim, she has chaired the working group on [[Domestic violence]], an expert crime-prevention group established by the [[:de:Hessisches Ministerium der Justiz|regional Ministry for Justice]].<ref name=HaeuslicheGewalt>{{cite web|title=Konfliktfeld Häusliche Gewalt: Transformationsprozesse und Perspektiven der Frauenhausarbeit|author= Margrit Brückner|date=23 March 2018|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007%2F978-3-658-20295-8_3|publisher= Springer International Publishing AG., CH-Cham|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>
== Celebrations == * 1984 [[:de:Elisabeth-Selbert-Preis|Elisabeth Selbert Prize]] for her doctoral dissertation, "''Die Liebe der Frauen....''"<ref name=LaudatioMSJueberMB>{{cite web|work=Tony Sender Preis 2013: Dokumentation| pages=11-17|title=Tony Sender Preis ... Laudatio von Monika Simmel-Joachim|date=September 2014|publisher=Frauenreferat Frankfurt am Main| url=https://www.frankfurt.de/sixcms/media.php/738/Dokumentation-Tony-Sender-Preis_2013.pdf|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> * 2008 [[Laura Bassi|Laura Maria Bassi Prize]] from the Frankfurt University of Applied Sciences<ref name=LaudatioMSJueberMB/> * 2013 [[:de:Tony-Sender-Preis|Tony Sender Prize]]<ref name=LaudatioSSueberMB>{{cite web|work=Tony Sender Preis 2013: Dokumentation| pages=5-9|title=Tony Sender Preis ... Rede von Statträtin Sarah Sorge|date=September 2014|publisher=Frauenreferat Frankfurt am Main|url=https://www.frankfurt.de/sixcms/media.php/738/Dokumentation-Tony-Sender-Preis_2013.pdf|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>
