In [[linguistics]], '''suprasegmentals''' are contrastive elements of speech that cannot be easily analyzed as distinct [[Segment (linguistics)|segment]]s but rather belong to a syllable or word. These elements include [[Intonation (linguistics)|intonation]], [[stress (linguistics)|stress]] and [[juncture]]. In some languages [[nasal vowel|nasality]] and [[vowel harmony]] are considered suprasegmental or [[Prosody (linguistics)|prosodic]] by some phonologists.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Palmer|first1=F.R.|title=Prosodic Analysis|date=1970|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Firth|first1=J.R.|title=Sounds and Prosodies|journal=Transactions of the Philological Society|date=1948|pages=127–52}}</ref>

