{{italic title}} '''''The Uses of Literacy''''' is a book written by [[Richard Hoggart]] and published in 1957, examining the [[influence of mass media]] in the United Kingdom. The book has been described as a key influence in the history of English and [[media studies]] and in the founding of [[cultural studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nate.org.uk/index.php?page=3&rev=164|title=Welcome - NATE|website=NATE|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ISBN=0415079063|title=Culture, media, language: working papers in cultural studies, 1972-79|first=Stuart|last=Hall|publisher=Routledge|year=1992}}</ref>
==Massification of culture== ''The Uses of Literacy'' was an attempt to understand the changes in [[British culture|culture in Britain]] caused by "massification". It has been described as marking a "watershed in public perception of culture and class and shifted academic parameters".<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|editor=Sue Owen|title=Richard Hoggart and Cultural Studies|year=2008|ISBN=9780230545458}}</ref> Hoggart's argument is that "the mass publicists" were made "more insistently, effectively and in a more comprehensive and centralised form today than they were earlier" and "that we are moving towards the creation of a mass culture, that the remnants of what was at least in part an urban culture 'of the people' are being destroyed".<ref name="librarything.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.librarything.com/work/15276|title=The Uses of Literacy by Richard Hoggart|website=LibraryThing.com|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>
==The "drift"== In his study Hoggart looks at [[pulp magazine|pulp fiction]], popular magazines and newspapers and the movies and finds in all of these, "drift". He documents the break-up of the old, class culture, lamenting the loss of the close-knit communities and their replacement by the emerging manufactured mass culture. Key features of this are the tabloid newspapers, advertising, and the triumph of Hollywood. These "alien" phenomena have colonized local communities and robbed them of their distinctive features. Hoggart's attack is not on popular culture; rather it is on mass culture which is imposed from above. "Popular culture" being self-created has a fundamental integrity and evolves according to its own laws and dictates, not as a result of the mass media.<ref name="librarything.com"/>
